### Critical

#### 1. Assertion-Free Test *(a.k.a. "Default Test")*
**Location:** `ProcessOrder_CompletesWithoutError` (line 43)  
**Catalog ref:** testsmells.org — *Assertion Free Test*

The test exercises `ProcessOrder` but never asserts anything. It will pass even if the method silently corrupts data, returns garbage, or changes its contract.

```csharp
// ❌ Before — always passes
processor.ProcessOrder(order);

// ✅ After — verify observable outcome
var result = processor.ProcessOrder(order);
Assert.AreEqual("StandardProcessed", result.Status);
Assert.IsTrue(_db.WasOrderSaved(order.Id));
```

---

### High

#### 2. Conditional Test Logic
**Location:** `ProcessOrder_SetsCorrectStatus` (lines 31–38)  
**Catalog ref:** testsmells.org — *Conditional Test Logic*

An `if/else` branch inside the test means only one assertion path is ever evaluated per run, and the test author may not know *which*. Tests should follow a single deterministic path.

```csharp
// ❌ Before — conditional branch
if (result.TotalAmount > 100)
    Assert.AreEqual("PremiumProcessed", result.Status);
else
    Assert.AreEqual("StandardProcessed", result.Status);

// ✅ After — split into two deterministic tests
[TestMethod]
public void ProcessOrder_StandardAmount_SetsStandardStatus()
{
    var order = new Order { Items = { new OrderItem("SKU-1", 1) } };
    var result = new OrderProcessor(_db, _email, _inventory).ProcessOrder(order);
    Assert.AreEqual("StandardProcessed", result.Status);
}

[TestMethod]
public void ProcessOrder_PremiumAmount_SetsPremiumStatus()
{
    var order = new Order { Items = { new OrderItem("SKU-EXPENSIVE", 10) } };
    var result = new OrderProcessor(_db, _email, _inventory).ProcessOrder(order);
    Assert.AreEqual("PremiumProcessed", result.Status);
}
```

#### 3. Sleepy Test
**Location:** `ProcessOrder_AsyncNotification_IsSent` (line 98)  
**Catalog ref:** testsmells.org — *Sleepy Test*

`Thread.Sleep(2000)` makes the test slow and flaky — it may not be long enough on CI, and wastes 2 s every run.

```csharp
// ❌ Before
processor.ProcessOrderAsync(order);
Thread.Sleep(2000);

// ✅ After — await the async method properly
await processor.ProcessOrderAsync(order);
// or use a deterministic synchronization primitive
```

#### 4. Exception Handling *(a.k.a. "Exception Catching & Throwing")*
**Location:** `ProcessOrder_EmptyOrder_ThrowsValidationError` (lines 110–118)  
**Catalog ref:** testsmells.org — *Exception Handling*

Manual `try/catch` + `Assert.Fail` is fragile. If a *different* exception type is thrown, the test crashes with an unhandled exception instead of a clean failure. MSTest v4 provides `Assert.ThrowsExactly` for this.

```csharp
// ❌ Before
try { processor.ProcessOrder(order); Assert.Fail("Expected exception"); }
catch (ValidationException ex) { Assert.AreEqual("Order must contain at least one item", ex.Message); }

// ✅ After
var ex = Assert.ThrowsExactly<ValidationException>(
    () => processor.ProcessOrder(order));
Assert.AreEqual("Order must contain at least one item", ex.Message);
```

#### 5. Mystery Guest
**Location:** `ImportOrders_FromCsv_ParsesCorrectly` (line 145)  
**Catalog ref:** testsmells.org — *Mystery Guest*

The test reads from `C:\TestData\orders.csv` — an external file whose contents are invisible in the test, platform-specific (Windows path), and almost certainly absent on CI.

```csharp
// ❌ Before
var orders = processor.ImportOrders(
    File.ReadAllText(@"C:\TestData\orders.csv"));

// ✅ After — inline the test data
const string csv = """
    SKU-1,2,49.99
    SKU-2,1,29.99
    SKU-3,3,15.00
    SKU-4,1,99.99
    SKU-5,2,12.50
    """;
var orders = processor.ImportOrders(csv);
Assert.AreEqual(5, orders.Count);
```

